{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638828"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:59:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:59:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17738"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17738"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.88,0,0.04,0,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10452"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72181"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10452"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57651"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10521"},{"type":"tags","id":"11222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24405"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72181"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of dysuria and increased urinary frequency. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A urinalysis is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following parameters is most likely to be elevated on the urinalysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Leukocyte esterase","Bilirubin","Ketones","Urobilinogen","Glucose"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the context of a urinary tract infection (UTI), the urinalysis is likely to show elevated \u003Cstrong\u003Eleukocyte esterase\u003C/strong\u003E, which indicates the presence of white blood cells in the urine, suggesting infection or inflammation. This is a common finding in UTIs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitrites\u003C/strong\u003E may also be elevated in UTIs, as certain bacteria convert nitrates to nitrites. However, not all bacteria produce nitrites, so this is not always present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood\u003C/strong\u003E may be present in the urine due to inflammation or infection of the urinary tract, but leukocyte esterase is a more direct indicator of infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eketones\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebilirubin\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eurobilinogen\u003C/strong\u003E are not typically elevated in UTIs. Glucose and ketones are more relevant to diabetes, while bilirubin and urobilinogen relate to liver function and haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urinary tract infections often present with elevated leukocytes, nitrites, and blood on urinalysis.","Leukocyte esterase indicates the presence of white blood cells, suggesting infection or inflammation.","Nitrites are produced by certain bacteria, indicating a bacterial infection.","Blood in the urine can occur due to inflammation or infection of the urinary tract."],"references":["Young JL, Soper DE. Urinalysis and urinary tract infection: update for clinicians. Infect Dis Obstet Gynecol. 2001;9(4):249-55. doi: 10.1155/S1064744901000412. PMID: 11916184; PMCID: PMC1784655.","Bono MJ, Leslie SW, Reygaert WC. Uncomplicated Urinary Tract Infections. [Updated 2023 Nov 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470195/","Semeniuk H, Church D. Evaluation of the leukocyte esterase and nitrite urine dipstick screening tests for detection of bacteriuria in women with suspected uncomplicated urinary tract infections. J Clin Microbiol. 1999 Sep;37(9):3051-2. doi: 10.1128/JCM.37.9.3051-3052.1999. PMID: 10449505; PMCID: PMC85454.","Tan CW, Chlebicki MP. Urinary tract infections in adults. Singapore Med J. 2016 Sep;57(9):485-90. doi: 10.11622/smedj.2016153. PMID: 27662890; PMCID: PMC5027397."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57651"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17738"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57651"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T01:53:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T01:54:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10452"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72181"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag